Furthermore, both new species can be easily diagnosed from other 

Araeoncus

species by the shape of palpal tibial apophyses (
Figs 1E
; 
4D
), which are not typical biforked shape as in 

A. humilis

(see 
Wiehle 1960
: fig. 431), by the presence of posterior radical process and mesal tooth of embolic division (
Figs 2E
; 
5D
) and by the postero-median triangular prolongations of the bisected epigynum (
Figs 3B
; 
5G
).
